"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714286","Department for Education","false","2017-03-30","<p>The Commission’s first full year of operation was 2013-14 and they have spent a total amount of £2,029,695 to date. This figure includes spend on commissioned research. To note that this is based on spend up until 29 March 2017 and does not cover full spend for 2016-17.</p>",,"Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714286/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-30T15:54:26.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714286/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714286/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-27","Social Mobility Commission","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much has been spent on the running of the Social Mobility Commission since it was first established as the Social Mobility and Child Poverty Commission.","false","Biography information for Lord Farmer",,"Lord Farmer","HL6307"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714287","Department for Education","false","2017-03-30","<p>The Commission’s first full year of operation was 2013-14 and they have spent a total of £337,913 on commissioned research to date. To note that this is based on spend up until 29 March 2017 and does not cover full spend for 2016-17.</p>",,"Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714287/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-30T15:54:43.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714287/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714287/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-27","Social Mobility Commission","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much has been spent on research commissioned by the Social Mobility Commission since it was first established as the Social Mobility and Child Poverty Commission.","false","Biography information for Lord Farmer",,"Lord Farmer","HL6308"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714288","Department for Education","false","2017-03-30","<p>We welcome the Commission’s ‘Helping parents to parent’ report, published in February. The report was commissioned by the Social Mobility Commission to bring together evidence on parenting behaviours and the extent to which public policy can support parents. It examined 28 interventions and programmes in the United Kingdom and internationally.</p><p>The research was tendered in an open competition process and the successful bid was put forward by the market and social research agency, Family Kids and Youth, which carried out the research. The amount for this research contract is £10,350 (exclusive of VAT) and this is in line with the total project spend.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714288/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-30T15:55:08.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714288/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714288/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-27","Child Rearing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much was spent by the Social Mobility Commission on preparing and publishing its report <i>Helping Parents to Parent</i>, published in February 2017.","false","Biography information for Lord Farmer",,"Lord Farmer","HL6309"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714289","HM Treasury","false","2017-04-07","<p>Productivity is a key determinant of GDP per head. As noted in the 2012 report by the Migration Advisory Committee (MAC), the empirical literature suggests that the impact of migration on aggregate productivity may be mixed and heavily dependent on the type of migrant coming to the UK. Migrants may increase productivity either through a simple ‘batting average’ effect if they work in higher productivity roles relative to the average for non-migrants, or through increasing the productivity of UK workers through greater specialisation and knowledge transfer.</p><p> </p><p>In this report, the MAC established the key role played by skilled migrants in raising productivity. Further, the 2014 MAC report, ‘Migrants in low-skilled work’, found low skilled migrants have a neutral impact on UK-born employment rates, GDP per head and productivity.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714289/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-07T12:37:02.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714289/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714289/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-27","EU Nationals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Neville-Rolfe on 23 March 2017 (HL5996), what estimate they have made of the contribution of non-UK EU nationals living in the UK to the UK’s gross domestic product per head; and what assessment they have made of that contribution.","false","Biography information for Lord Green of Deddington",,"Lord Green of Deddington","HL6310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714290","Home Office","false","2017-03-31","<p>Information on Tier 4 (General) grants for Indian nationals is published quarterly; latest data in the Home Office’s ‘Immigration Statistics, October - December 2016’, Visa data tables volume 3, table vi_06_q_s, available from the <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-october-to-december-2016/list-of-tables#visas" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-october-to-december-2016/list-of-tables#visas</a></p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714290/answer","entry visas 3 - q4 tables vol 3 - table vi-06-q-s.xlsx","entry visas 3 - q4 tables vol 3 - table vi-06-q-s.xlsx","Table vi-06-q-s- Immigration Stats - Oct-Dec 2016 ","Table vi-06-q-s- Immigration Stats - Oct-Dec 2016 ",,"2017-03-31T11:10:05.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714290/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714290/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-27","Entry Clearances: India","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many Tier 4 (General) student visas were granted to Indian nationals in each year since 2001.","false","Biography information for Lord Green of Deddington",,"Lord Green of Deddington","HL6311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714291","Home Office","false","2017-04-06","<p>The UK Border Agency stopped accepting Tier 4 applications from North India in February 2010 owing to concerns about fraudulent applications. The rules on the policy were strengthened during 2010 and the acceptance of applications resumed in August of that year.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714291/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-06T10:47:12.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714291/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714291/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-27","Entry Clearances: India","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government for what periods in 2009 and 2010 did the then UK Border Agency stop accepting new applications for a Tier 4 (General) student visa in North India.","false","Biography information for Lord Green of Deddington",,"Lord Green of Deddington","HL6312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714292","Home Office","false","2017-03-30","<p>I am sorry but the information requested is not included in statistics published by the Home Office.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714292/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-30T15:19:46.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714292/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714292/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-27","Visas: Overseas Students","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many applicants for a Tier 4 (General) student visa, or its previous equivalent, have been interviewed as part of the application process in each year since 2006.","false","Biography information for Lord Green of Deddington",,"Lord Green of Deddington","HL6313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714293","Home Office","false","2017-04-06","<p>Quarterly information on the total number of Tier 4 (General) student visas refused is published in Visa table vi_01_q, and the total number of Indian nationals refused a visa (all categories) in table vi_02_q. The latest data are in the Home Office’s ‘Immigration Statistics, October - December 2016’, (Visa data tables volume1) available from the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-october-to-december-2016/list-of-tables#visas" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-october-to-december-2016/list-of-tables#visas</a></p><p>The relevant tables have also been attached to this answer.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714293/answer","Student Visas Refused.xls ; Indian Visa Applications.xls","Student Visas Refused.xls ; Indian Visa Applications.xls","Student Visas ; Indian Visas","Student Visas ; Indian Visas",,"2017-04-06T10:48:45.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714293/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/714293/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-27","Entry Clearances: India","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many applications for a Tier 4 (General) student visa from Indian nationals were refused in each year from 2006 to 2016; what was the rate of refusal; how many appeals were lodged against refusals; and what number were subsequently allowed.","false","Biography information for Lord Green of Deddington",,"Lord Green of Deddington","HL6314"
