"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713401","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-28","<p>The period of account for 2016-17 closes on 31 March for Corporation Tax and VAT payers and 5 April for individuals. Relevant receipts data for these measures in this year is not yet available and will be finalised over the following months.</p><p>The estimated tax revenue impacts in 2017-18 for these measures were not changed at Budget 2017 from those previously published.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713401/answer",,,,,"68830 ; 68833","2017-03-28T16:45:10.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713401/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713401/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-23","Tax Yields","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to table 2.1, line 39 of the Budget 2016, how much additional tax was raised in 2016-17 under that measure; and what estimate he has made of the change to the 2017-18 tax level against the baseline projection contained in that table.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","68834"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713402","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-28","<p>The dividend allowance came into effect in April 2016. Dividend income is reported through self-assessment and HM Revenue and Customs will not receive self-assessment data for 2016-17 until January 2018. This data is therefore not currently available.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713402/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-28T15:58:51.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713402/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713402/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-23","Investment Income: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people in each tax band used the dividend allowance in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","68836"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713403","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-30","<p>Air Passenger Duty (APD) is a tax levied only on airline operators. Small commercial airfields and airports are not liable to pay the duty. The Government recognises the contribution of the aviation industry and, as with all parts of the tax system, continues to keep APD under careful review.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713403/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-30T13:57:46.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713403/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713403/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-23","Air Passenger Duty","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of air passenger duty on small commercial airfields.","false","Biography information for Glyn Davies","Montgomeryshire","Glyn Davies","68849"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713404","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-30","<p>Merchants currently pay a merchant service charge to process all card transactions. Part of this covers the fees that a merchant acquirer can be charged by a card issuing bank for processing transactions known as interchange fees. The Interchange Fee Regulation (IFR), which came into force in December 2015, caps the fees that could be passed on to consumers from merchants in the form of higher prices at 0.2% and 0.3% for debit and credit cards respectively.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has been clear that it would like to see merchants passing on these savings to their customers so that they continue to benefit from the interchange fee caps.</p><p> </p><p>From January 2018, the Payment Services Directive 2 introduces a ban on surcharging which means that retailers will no longer be able to charge consumers to use payment instruments for which interchange fees are regulated, which includes the majority of consumer debit and credit cards.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713404/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-30T13:55:00.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713404/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713404/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-23","Bank Cards: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make it his policy to encourage retailers to abolish charges for customers using card payments for transactions.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","68967"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713405","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-28","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy provides funding to Citizen Advice (CitA), the umbrella body for the Citizen Advice Service in England and Wales through an annual grant to support their core function and to deliver consumer advocacy and advice. Funding over the last three years is set out in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>BIS Core Funding</p></td><td><p>Consumer advice, information &amp; advocacy</p></td><td><p>Total Funding</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>£18,900,000</p></td><td><p>£19,974,300</p></td><td><p><strong>£38,874,300</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>£18,900,000</p></td><td><p>£19,313,300</p></td><td><p><strong>£38,213,300</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£18,900,000</p></td><td><p>£18,940,300</p></td><td><p><strong>£37,840,300</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Central Government does not provide funding directly to local individual Citizen Advice offices, core funding for which is usually provided by the local authority in which they are located.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713405/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-28T14:23:07.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713405/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713405/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-23","Citizens' Advice Bureaux","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will make an assessment of the effect of changes in the level of Government funding for the Citizens Advice Service in (a) England, (b) West Yorkshire and (c) Kirklees in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","69046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713406","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-29","<p>The Department published the allocations for the distribution of the additional funding for adult social care announced at the Spring Budget 2017 online on 9 March, together with an Explanatory Note concerning distribution. This is available at :</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-allocations-of-the-additional-funding-for-adult-social-care" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-allocations-of-the-additional-funding-for-adult-social-care</a>.</p><p>The funding will be made available from April 2017.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713406/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-29T14:21:58.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713406/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713406/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-03-23","Social Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to paragraph 6.1 of the Spring Budget 2017, what criteria will be used to allocate the additional £2 billion for social care to councils; and when that funding will be made available.","false","Biography information for Corri Wilson","Ayr, Carrick and Cumnock","Corri Wilson","68850"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713407","Department of Health","false","2017-03-30","<p>There are no plans to do so. There are a range of services available to problem gamblers, details of which can be found on the NHS Choices website at:</p><p><a href="http://www.nhs.uk/Livewell/addiction/Pages/gamblingaddiction.aspx" target="_blank">www.nhs.uk/Livewell/addiction/Pages/gamblingaddiction.aspx</a></p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713407/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-30T13:46:04.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713407/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713407/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-03-23","Gambling: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if the Government will produce a strategy to provide NHS support for problem gamblers who wish to receive anonymous treatment.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","68853"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713408","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-31","<p>The Gambling (Licensing and Advertising Act) 2014 brought offshore online gambling operators within scope of the Gambling Commission’s regulatory regime for the first time.</p><p> </p><p>Since then, the Commission has introduced a number of additional licence conditions in relation to online. These new requirements include providing easily accessible facilities for consumers to impose their own limits, which can include limits on deposit, spend and losses, and over different time durations.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, a new multi-operator online self-exclusion scheme, which will allow individuals to simultaneously self exclude from all online gambling sites, will be introduced by the industry later this year.</p><p> </p><p>We keep the regulation of online gambling under review and will not hesitate to take action if it is needed to protect people from gambling-related harm.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713408/answer",,,,,"68855","2017-03-31T12:28:55.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713408/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713408/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-23","Gambling: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if she will introduce a limit for online gamblers that applies on all platforms.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","68854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713409","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-31","<p>The Gambling (Licensing and Advertising Act) 2014 brought offshore online gambling operators within scope of the Gambling Commission’s regulatory regime for the first time.</p><p> </p><p>Since then, the Commission has introduced a number of additional licence conditions in relation to online. These new requirements include providing easily accessible facilities for consumers to impose their own limits, which can include limits on deposit, spend and losses, and over different time durations.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, a new multi-operator online self-exclusion scheme, which will allow individuals to simultaneously self exclude from all online gambling sites, will be introduced by the industry later this year.</p><p> </p><p>We keep the regulation of online gambling under review and will not hesitate to take action if it is needed to protect people from gambling-related harm.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713409/answer",,,,,"68854","2017-03-31T12:28:55.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713409/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713409/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-23","Gambling: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what plans the Government has to produce a strategy to better limit the maximum stakes for online gambling.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","68855"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713410","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-31","<p>The protection of children from being harmed or exploited by gambling is one of the core objectives of the Gambling Act 2005.</p><p> </p><p>Gambling Commission licence conditions ensure strict controls are in place to prevent children from accessing gambling online. Where there is a failure to prevent underage gambling, the Gambling Commission will take regulatory and/or criminal action.</p><p>Government will not hesitate to take action if it is needed to protect young people from gambling-related harm.</p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713410/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-31T12:21:13.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713410/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713410/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-23","Gambling: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps she is taking to ensure that under-age people are not able to gamble online.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","68856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713411","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-28","<p>Two officials from my Department were core members of the Expert Working Group established in October 2014. Since the group's report was published in January 2016, they are continuing to work with the football authorities and supporter representative groups to drive forward its recommendations as part of their wider duties.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713411/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-28T15:07:55.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713411/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713411/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-23","Football Supporter Ownership and Engagement Expert Working Group: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate she has made of the number of full-time equivalent civil servants working on the Government Expert Working Group on Football Supporter Ownership and Engagement since that working group was founded; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","68885"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713412","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-28","<p>My Department has provided no funding. I am indebted to the independent Chair, Joanna Manning-Cooper, and the other group members, who undertook their roles on a voluntary basis.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713412/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-28T15:08:30.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713412/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713412/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-23","Football Supporter Ownership and Engagement Expert Working Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what the total amount of direct funding her Department has provided to support the activities of the Government Expert Working Group on Football Supporter Ownership and Engagement since that working group was founded; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","68886"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713413","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-28","<p>I refer the Hon. member to the answer to PQ 68246.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713413/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-28T15:07:20.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713413/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713413/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-23","Football","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what progress has been made in implementing recommendations in the Government Expert Working Group on Football Supporter Ownership and Engagement: Final Report: November 2015, published 19 January 2016; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","68883"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713414","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-03","<p>The information requested about these museums' collections is not available at this level of detail, due to their size and complexity. However, the British Museum and the British Library do hold significant artefacts with a connection to the North East of England, such as the Vindolanda Tablets in the BM and the Lindisfarne Gospels in the BL.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713414/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-03T08:34:59.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713414/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713414/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-23","Cultural Heritage: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many artefacts and items held by the (a) National Gallery, (b) British Museum and (c) British Library relate to or have their origin in the North East of England.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","68932"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713415","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-28","<p>My Department has regular discussions with other Government Departments on a range of issues impacting on the regulation of the telecoms sector and regularly receives proposals which contribute to policy development, which are considered on their merits as part of this process.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713415/answer",,,,,"69008","2017-03-28T11:11:00.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713415/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713415/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-23","Telecommunications: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions her Department has had with other departments on whether Ofcom's Dark Fibre Access regulatory remedy is affected by the application of business rates on electronic communications providers purchasing Dark Fibre Access from BT Openreach when it becomes available in October 2017.","false","Biography information for Calum Kerr","Berwickshire, Roxburgh and Selkirk","Calum Kerr","68946"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713416","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-31","<p>We are currently developing the scope and membership of the Digital Skills Partnership.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713416/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-31T10:41:04.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713416/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713416/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-23","Digital Technology: Great Grimsby","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 9 March 2017 to Question 66060, on Digital Technology: Great Grimsby, which companies have committed to working in Great Grimsby as part of the Digital Skills Partnership.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","69016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713417","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-04-26","<p>A breakdown of media spend by advertising platform for the Go Superfast campaign is as below:</p><p> </p><p>Television £2,398,000</p><p>Video on Demand £284,000</p><p>Out of Home (posters) £2,000,000</p><p>Press (national and regional) £828,000</p><p>Radio £300,000</p><p>Digital £928,000</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Department spent £987,620.34 on production costs.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713417/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-26T09:14:36.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713417/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713417/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-23","Broadband: Advertising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how much she has spent on each advertising platform by the Go Superfast advertising campaign.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","69037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713418","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-28","<p>National Citizen Service (NCS) funding allocations for the years 2016-17 onwards were made at the 2015 Spending Review and revised in 2017. At Spending Review 2015 the Barnett Formula was applied in the normal way to spending allocations of UK Government departments and not to individual spending programmes such as NCS.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713418/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-28T15:10:41.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713418/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713418/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-23","Voluntary Work: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what the value is of Barnett consequential funding allocated to the Scottish Parliament as a result of National Citizenship Service funding.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","68991"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713419","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-31","<p>Historic England maintains a national Heritage at Risk Register that includes details of all Grade I and II* listed buildings at risk, plus details of Grade II listed buildings at risk in London and Grade II listed places of worship at risk outside London. In relation to buildings on the Register, Historic England operates a grant scheme for project development and urgent structural repairs, and provides advice to owners, developers and local authorities on changes, plus other sources of funding and advice. Such sources include the Heritage Lottery Fund, which has awarded over £90 million towards projects in the North East primarily focused on listed buildings. These projects typically focus on repair and redevelopment, but can also include funding for other activities such as engagement which help ensure the long term sustainability of a project.</p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713419/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-31T12:22:36.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713419/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713419/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-23","Historic Buildings: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps she is taking to ensure that buildings in the North East on the National Heritage List for England are properly maintained.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","68961"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713420","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-31","<p>Government funding for tourism, which is dispersed through VisitBritain and VisitEngland, is not allocated regionally but instead focuses on promoting the country as a whole and thematically. It is not possible to ascertain the precise figures for funding given to the different regions across England.</p><p> </p><p>Other streams of non-central Government funding, including funding from local authorities and businesses, also supports tourism at a local level.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713420/answer",,,,,"68979 ; 68981","2017-03-31T12:25:17.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713420/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713420/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-23","Tourism: Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of tourism funding has been allocated to the Midlands in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Amanda Milling","Cannock Chase","Amanda Milling","68980"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713421","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-31","<p>Government funding for tourism, which is dispersed through VisitBritain and VisitEngland, is not allocated regionally but instead focuses on promoting the country as a whole and thematically. It is not possible to ascertain the precise figures for funding given to the different regions across England.</p><p> </p><p>Other streams of non-central Government funding, including funding from local authorities and businesses, also supports tourism at a local level.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713421/answer",,,,,"68979 ; 68980","2017-03-31T12:25:17.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713421/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713421/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-23","Tourism: Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of English tourism funding is allocated to the Midlands.","false","Biography information for Amanda Milling","Cannock Chase","Amanda Milling","68981"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713422","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-31","<p>Tourism provides more than £62bn of GVA to the UK economy and one in ten jobs are in the tourism industries. The Government Tourism Action Plan which aims to increase international visits outside of London, will ensure the economic benefit of tourism is felt across the country.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713422/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-31T12:27:19.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713422/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713422/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-23","Tourism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate the Government has made of the economic value of tourism.","false","Biography information for Amanda Milling","Cannock Chase","Amanda Milling","68982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713423","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-30","<p>Ofcom have issued 123 licences since 2010, bringing the total number of stations broadcasting around the UK since 2004 to 245, with a further 31 preparing to start. For a breakdown of licences issued since 2010 see as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Licences Awarded</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>13</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>24</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>23</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>22</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>123</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713423/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-30T12:16:46.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713423/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713423/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-03-23","Local Broadcasting: Radio","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many community radio licences for FM broadcast have been granted by Ofcom in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Amanda Milling","Cannock Chase","Amanda Milling","68978"
