 was collected by Form 618g and the full-time equivalent number of teaching assistants and support staff were collected by the School Census. From 2010 onwards, information on all school employees was collected in the annual School Workforce Census.</p><p>[2] The hours worked by school support staff were not collected in the 2010 School Workforce Census so a full-time equivalent figure is not available.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713444/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-29T14:14:25.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713444/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713444/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-23","Schools: York","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many full-time equivalent (a) teachers, (b) teaching assistants and (c) support staff there were in local authority schools in the City of York in each year since 2005.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","68865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713445","Department for Education","false","2017-03-28","<p>Pupil premium grant allocations, including for the service child pupil premium, for each parliamentary constituency are published annually. The most recent publication is the department’s pupil premium allocations and conditions of grant 2016 to 2017 guidance in June 2016: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/541198/2016-17_National___LA___PC_tables_-_v2.xlsx" target="_blank">Pupil premium final allocations 2016 to 2017 by local authority area and region in England</a>.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713445/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-28T15:41:25.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713445/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713445/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-23","Service Pupil Premium","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many children in each parliamentary constituency have been in receipt of the service pupil premium in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","68874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713446","Department for Education","false","2017-03-28","<p>The Children and Families Act 2014, regulations made under that Act, and the Special Educational Needs and Disability (SEND) Code of Practice introduced significant reforms to the SEND system in England. The reforms need time to bed in, and we are providing local areas with support to allow them to implement them effectively. We are also gathering feedback from a wide range of individuals and organisations. In due course, and in the light of that feedback, we will review the existing Code and regulations.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713446/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-28T15:43:37.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713446/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713446/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-23","Special Educational Needs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will make an assessment of the potential merits of bringing forward legislative proposals to support parents with special needs children to access appropriate education that meets the individual needs of those children.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","68929"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713447","Department for Education","false","2017-04-04","<p>To be awarded qualified teacher status (QTS), all teachers must be able to meet the Teachers’ Standards at the appropriate level. The standards require teachers to have a clear understanding of the needs of all pupils, including those with special educational needs (SEN) and must be able to adapt teaching to the needs of all pupils, as well as have an understanding of the factors that can inhibit learning and how to overcome them.</p><p>The Government, does not prescribe the content or structure of training courses, and does not maintain a record of the hours of training provided to newly qualified teachers by topics. Teacher-training providers and schools are in the best position to judge these in line with the newly qualified teacher’s developmental requirement and local need.</p><p>To help support schools and teachers identify and participate in the most effective development activities, the Government published a new Standard for Teachers’ Professional Development in July 2016.</p><p>The standard can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/standard-for-teachers-professional-development" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/standard-for-teachers-professional-development</a>.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713447/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-04T11:09:29.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713447/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713447/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-23","Special Educational Needs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many hours of training in supporting children with special needs newly qualified teachers receive.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","68930"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713448","Department for Education","false","2017-03-30","<p>A revised version of the Ministerial Code was published on 21 December 2016, which removed the provisions for setting up Extended Ministerial Offices (EMOs).</p><p>In line with the changes we are disbanding the Secretary of State’s Extended Ministerial Office (EMO), which has until now comprised 6 civil servants, with a payroll cost for the 2016-17 financial year (excluding March 2017) of £458,113.94 (including National Insurance and pension contributions).</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713448/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-30T09:18:57.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713448/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713448/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-23","Department for Education: Extended Ministerial Offices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many civil servants work in her Extended Ministerial Office; and what the total payroll cost is of that Office in the 2016-17 financial year.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","69042"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713449","Department for Education","false","2017-03-28","<p>The Education in the Media blog is run by the Department’s Communications team.</p><p>The Department incurs no direct cost for the maintenance of the Education in the Media blog.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713449/answer",,,,,"69044","2017-03-28T11:18:25.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713449/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713449/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-23","Department for Education: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much her Department has spent maintaining the Education in the media blog on its departmental website.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","69043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713450","Department for Education","false","2017-03-28","<p>The Education in the Media blog is run by the Department’s Communications team.</p><p>The Department incurs no direct cost for the maintenance of the Education in the Media blog.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713450/answer",,,,,"69043","2017-03-28T11:18:25.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713450/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713450/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-23","Department for Education: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, which members of her Department's staff work on the Education in the media blog on its departmental website.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","69044"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713451","Department for Education","false","2017-03-30","<p>In September 2015, Universities UK was asked by Government to set up a sexual violence and harassment taskforce<strong>. </strong>The Taskforce reported its findings in October 2016 in the report ‘<a href="http://www.universitiesuk.ac.uk/policy-and-analysis/reports/Documents/2016/changing-the-culture.pdf" target="_blank">Changing the Culture</a>’.</p><p>The Taskforce’s report draws on the available data and evidence to make a series of recommendations on preventing and responding to sexual harassment. The Taskforce report establishes there is no single source of data on the levels of sexual harassment on University campuses. The Taskforce plans to establish more baseline evidence on this issue and report later this year.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713451/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-30T09:54:44.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713451/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713451/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-23","Students: Sexual Harassment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what information her Department holds on the number of students who have reported incidents of sexual harassment or threat in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","68971"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713452","Department for Education","false","2017-03-28","<p>The Department does not hold directly comparable data for the numbers of children’s centres each year.</p><p> </p><p>As at 24 March 2017 based on information supplied by local authorities, there were 3,210 main children’s centres and sites open to families and children as part of a network.</p><p> </p><p>We know that the total number of main children’s centres and sites at April 2010[1] was 3,615.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Councils are merging centres to allow services to be delivered more efficiently. Where they decide to close a children’s centre, councils must demonstrate that children and families, particularly the most disadvantaged, will not be adversely affected and that they will not compromise their duty to have sufficient children’s centres to meet local need.</p><p>Records of children’s centres and sites are maintained by local authorities via the Department’s EduBase portal at:</p><p><a href="http://www.education.gov.uk/edubase/search.xhtml?clear=true" target="_blank">http://www.education.gov.uk/edubase/search.xhtml?clear=true</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>[1] We do not hold records of numbers of children’s centres prior to April 2010. It is not possible to give a year on year breakdown.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713452/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-28T11:19:09.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713452/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713452/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-23","Children's Centres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many Sure Start children's centres there were in England at the end of each calendar year from 2009; and how many there were on the last date for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","69023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713453","Department for Education","false","2017-03-29","<p>School funding is at its highest level on record at more than £40bn in 2016-17 - and that is set to rise, as pupil numbers rise over the next two years, to £42 billion by 2019-20. Analysis by the Institute for Financial Studies (IFS) has also shown that spending per pupil almost doubled in real terms between 1997 and 2016.</p><p> </p><p>We recognise that schools are facing cost pressures, and we estimate that, nationally, they amount to approximately an 8% cumulative pressure, per pupil, between the start of 2016-17 and 2019-20. It is important to note that some of these pressures have already materialised; 8% is not an estimate of pressures still to come. Over the next three years, per pupil pressures will, on average, be between 1.5-1.6%, each year.</p><p> </p><p>The National Audit Office report on the Financial Sustainability of Schools details the level of costs pressures on schools, based on the Department’s estimates: <a href="https://www.nao.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/Financial-sustainability-of-schools.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.nao.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/Financial-sustainability-of-schools.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>We will continue to provide advice and support to help them use their funding in cost effective ways, and improve the way they buy goods and services, so‎ they get the best possible value for their pupils. We have produced tools, information and guidance for schools financial health and efficiency, which can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/schools-financial-health-and-efficiency" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/schools-financial-health-and-efficiency</a>.</p><p><strong><br> </strong></p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713453/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-29T14:13:57.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713453/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713453/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-23","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to paragraph 3.6 of her Department's consultation, Schools national funding formula, Government consultation - stage 2, what the evidential basis is for the assessment of cost pressures on schools.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","69024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713454","Department for Education","false","2017-03-29","<p>In November 2015, there were 10,500 equivalent teachers aged 60 and over employed in state funded schools in England. This represents 2.3 percent of all full-time equivalent teachers in England. These figures are derived from the November 2015 School Workforce Census.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713454/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-29T14:15:03.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713454/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713454/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-23","Teachers: Older Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many teachers over the age of 60 were employed in schools in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","69000"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713455","Department for Education","false","2017-03-28","<p>Information about the number and proportion of pupils known to be eligible for free school meals in each individual school, along with the school’s admissions policy and it’s local authority area can be found in the underlying data accompanying the ‘Schools, pupils and their characteristics: January 2016’ statistics[1] publication.</p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2016</a></p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713455/answer",,,,,"69028","2017-03-28T15:15:14.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713455/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713455/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-23","Pupils: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many pupils are eligible for free school meals in selective schools in (a) Cumbria, (b) Lancashire, (c) Liverpool, (d) Trafford, (e) Wirral, (f) Calderdale, (g) Kirklees, (h) North Yorkshire, (i) Lincolnshire, (j) Birmingham, (k) Stoke-on-Trent, (l) Telford and Wrekin, (m) Walsall, (n) Warwickshire, (o) Wolverhampton, (p) Essex, (q) Southend-on-Sea, (r) Buckinghamshire, (s) Kent, (t) Medway, (u) Reading, (v) Slough, (w) Bournemouth, (x) Devon, (y) Gloucestershire, (z) Plymouth, (aa) Poole, (bb) Torbay, (cc) Wiltshire, (dd) Barnet, (ee) Bexley, (ff) Bromley, (gg) Enfield, (hh) Kingston upon Thames, (ii) Redbridge and (jj) Sutton.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","69027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713456","Department for Education","false","2017-03-28","<p>Information about the number and proportion of pupils known to be eligible for free school meals in each individual school, along with the school’s admissions policy and it’s local authority area can be found in the underlying data accompanying the ‘Schools, pupils and their characteristics: January 2016’ statistics[1] publication.</p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2016</a></p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713456/answer",,,,,"69027","2017-03-28T15:15:14.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713456/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713456/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-23","Grammar Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many pupils attend a selective school in (a) Cumbria, (b) Lancashire, (c) Liverpool, (d) Trafford, (e) Wirral, (f) Calderdale, (g) Kirklees, (h) North Yorkshire, (i) Lincolnshire, (j) Birmingham, (k) Stoke-on-Trent, (l) Telford and Wrekin, (m) Walsall, (n) Warwickshire, (o) Wolverhampton, (p) Essex, (q) Southend-on-Sea, (r) Buckinghamshire, (s) Kent, (t) Medway, (u) Reading, (v) Slough, (w) Bournemouth, (x) Devon, (y) Gloucestershire, (z) Plymouth, (aa) Poole, (bb) Torbay, (cc) Wiltshire, (dd) Barnet, (ee) Bexley, (ff) Bromley, (gg) Enfield, (hh) Kingston upon Thames, (ii) Redbridge and (jj) Sutton.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","69028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713457","Department for Education","false","2017-03-29","<p>Information on the number of teachers taking up new posts is not available. The following table provides the number and percentage of full-time equivalent teachers aged 60 and over in each year between 2011 and 2015.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>FTE Teachers aged 60 and over (thousands)</p></td><td><p>Percentage of all FTE Teachers aged 60 and over</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p>10.8</p></td><td><p>2.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p>11.0</p></td><td><p>2.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p>11.5</p></td><td><p>2.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p>10.9</p></td><td><p>2.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p>10.5</p></td><td><p>2.3</p></td></tr></tbody></table><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Source: School Workforce Census</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713457/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-29T14:15:30.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713457/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713457/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-03-23","Teachers: Older Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the numbers of teachers aged over 60 taking up new posts within schools in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","68998"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713458","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-28","<p>We are committed to publishing both a 25 year environment plan and food and farming plan during this Parliament to support our twin ambitions of being the first generation to leave the natural environment of England in a better state than that in which we found it, and to become a world leading food, farming and fishing nation: to grow more, sell more and export more British food. The plans are closely linked and we are starting a period of extensive engagement with a wide range of stakeholders to inform development of the full plans.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713458/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-28T11:46:27.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713458/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713458/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-23","Agriculture and Environment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent progress her Department has made on the 25 year (a) food and farming plan and (b) environment plan; and what the timetable is for the publication of each such plan.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","69026"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713459","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-31","<p>Information on nutrition is mandatory for most pre-packaged foods. Exemptions to this are listed in Annex V of the Regulation on the provision of food information to consumers, EU 1169/2011. Exemptions include unprocessed single ingredient products; food presented in very small packaging; and food (including handcrafted food) supplied by a manufacturer of small quantities of products, either directly to the final consumer or to local retail establishments directly supplying the final consumer.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713459/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-31T10:41:15.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713459/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713459/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-23","Food: Labelling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether food labelling in respect of sugar and fat content applies to all packaged foods and snacks available in retail outlets.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","68950"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713460","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-28","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the reply given to the hon. Member for Coventry South, Mr Jim Cunningham, on 1 March 2017, PQ UIN 65497.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713460/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-28T10:25:47.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713460/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713460/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-23","Squirrels: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will take steps to ensure the survival of the red squirrel over the course of the 2015 Parliament.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","68910"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713461","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-31","<p>Mandatory requirements for origin labelling already exist for a number of foods, such as beef, lamb, poultry and pork. Rules on origin labelling are not in place for dairy and processed meat products, such as bacon and burgers, but this is often provided on a voluntary basis. Most dairy and processed meat products are compliant with industry's voluntary principles for origin labelling and we are considering how to build on these voluntary principles. We also have an opportunity on leaving the EU to consider further extensions of mandatory country of origin labelling.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713461/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-31T10:45:17.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713461/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713461/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-23","Food: Origin Marking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans her Department have for improving information on food labelling and origin.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","68852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713462","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-29","<p>The Environment Agency has the equivalent of approximately 180 full-time officers who investigate all types of waste offences, including any relating to end of waste.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to tackling waste crime:</p><ul><li>In 2015/16 the Environment Agency spent £14.8 million tackling waste crime.</li><li>Approximately £23 million was allocated to the Environment Agency in the 2015 Spending Review specifically for tackling waste crime in England.</li></ul>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713462/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-29T13:42:52.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713462/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713462/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-23","Environment Agency: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many officials in the Environment Agency are employed to investigate businesses that are believed to have committed end of waste offences.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","68862"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713463","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-29","<p>The Government is aware of the devastating effect that dog attacks on livestock can have for farmers and other livestock keepers including in terms of significant financial loss. Data on the total costs are not collected centrally. Defra and the Animal Health and Welfare Board for England (AHWBE) recently met police forces, farming and rural interests to discuss the situation. Under the auspices of the National Police Chiefs’ Council, five police forces are collaborating to pilot more systematic data collection of incidents and good response practices.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713463/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-29T10:03:34.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713463/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713463/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-23","Livestock: Dogs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate she has made of the total cost to farmers in (a) the UK and (b) Yorkshire of dog attacks to livestock.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","68892"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713464","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-28","<p>In the most recently published figures the UK production to supply ratio for all food is 61% and for indigenous food 76%. These figures have been relatively constant over the previous 10 years.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>All food %</p></td><td><p>Indigenous type food %</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005</p></td><td><p>60</p></td><td><p>73</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006</p></td><td><p>59</p></td><td><p>72</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007</p></td><td><p>60</p></td><td><p>73</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008</p></td><td><p>60</p></td><td><p>73</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>59</p></td><td><p>72</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>61</p></td><td><p>75</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>64</p></td><td><p>78</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>63</p></td><td><p>77</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>60</p></td><td><p>73</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>62</p></td><td><p>76</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>61</p></td><td><p>76</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Production to Supply ratio is published annually in the “Agriculture in the UK” statistical publication.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713464/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-28T11:42:48.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713464/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713464/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-23","Food Supply","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment her Department has made of the level of the UK's self-sufficiency in food in each of the last 10 years; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","68828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713465","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-29","<p>We are currently analysing all EU fisheries legislation. No decision has yet been made on the extent to which the EU legislation governing the Common Fisheries Policy will be incorporated into domestic law.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713465/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-29T13:49:09.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713465/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713465/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-23","Fisheries: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether EU fisheries regulation 1380/2013 will be rewritten in order to be transposed into UK domestic legislation.","false","Biography information for Kevin Hollinrake","Thirsk and Malton","Kevin Hollinrake","68842"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713466","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-31","<p>The AHDB promotes British agricultural produce both domestically and overseas. The annual budget of the AHDB is approximately £60 million. We are also working with industry to identify opportunities to open new markets after leaving the EU and to support farm businesses that want to develop brands around food provenance.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713466/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-31T10:48:57.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713466/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713466/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-03-23","Agricultural Products and Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department is taking to increase consumer awareness of British-sourced and farmed produce and food after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","68848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713467","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-31","<p>Prior to the annoucement of the new Executive Order, I discussed the matter with the US Secretary for Homeland Security, General Kelly, at the Munich Security Conference on 17 February. General Kelly provided assurances that the new order would not affect British passport holders.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713467/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-31T13:18:33.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713467/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713467/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-23","USA: Travel Restrictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his US counterpart on the new Executive Order implementing a travel ban on people from six countries and on refugees.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","68845"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713468","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-30","<p>Our Deputy Ambassador to Tel Aviv met with Israel’s Europe Director on 13 March to discuss the new immigration law, and we continue to push for clarification from Israel on the impact on British nationals.</p><p>The British Government is strongly opposed to the Boycotts, Divestment and Sanctions Movement against Israel. But we believe the best way to combat this movement is through argument rather than legislation.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713468/answer",,,,,,"2017-03-30T13:35:12.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713468/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713468/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-23","Israel: Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to the Israeli Government on recent proposed changes to its immigration policy and procedures; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","68841"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713469","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-31","<p>We share the concerns of the international community about the deteriorating political and economic situation in Venezuela. Economic mismanagement is producing inflation and shortages of basic goods, with a significant impact upon ordinary Venezuelans. Venezuela became an FCO Human Rights Priority Country in 2016. President Maduro has requested United Nations assistance to boost medical supplies.</p><p>The Organisation of American States (OAS) has called for the OAS Democratic Charter to be invoked unless the Venezuelan Government calls elections and releases political prisoners. The UNASUR- supported dialogue between the Government and opposition has stalled.</p><p>I met the previous Venezuelan Minister for Europe, Samuel Moncada at the EU-CELAC Foreign Minister's meeting on 26 October and discussed humanitarian issues and the economic situation. At that meeting I also raised the deteriorating situation in Venezuela with several of my Latin American and European counterparts. On 20 March I met a delegation of Venezuelan MPs from the National Assembly to discuss the situation and to highlight our support for an independent and empowered Parliament. The EU Foreign Affairs Committee last discussed Venezuela on 18 July, which was attended by the Foreign Secretary.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713469/answer",,,,,"68905 ; 68906 ; 68907 ; 68908","2017-03-31T13:38:43.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713469/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713469/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-03-23","Venezuela: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the political and economic situation in Venezuela.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Sir Hugo Swire","68904"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713470","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-03","<p>The European Commission has proposed a multilateral investment court (MIC) to replace traditional investment dispute settlement mechanisms in individual trade and investment agreements. This initiative is at an early stage and there are as yet no detailed proposals regarding how a MIC would function or be resourced.</p><p>The Government is engaging with EU institutions and member states through the Council as the proposal is developed. The European Commission has recently completed a public consultation on the MIC. The Government encouraged key stakeholders from across the civil society, business, arbitration and legal communities to engage in this exercise.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713470/answer",,,,,"68868 ; 68869 ; 68870","2017-04-03T08:18:09.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713470/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/713470/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-03-23","Foreign Investment: Dispute Resolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what representations his Department has received from civil society organisations on the EU's proposed multilateral investment court.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","68867"
